<div class="ingredients">
    <h3><strong>Ingredients</strong></h3>
    <ul>
        <li>1/2 teaspoon baking soda</li>
        <li>4 pounds Russet or Yukon Gold potatoes, peeled and cut into desired bite-sized pieces (do larger pieces than you might think, as they will shring)</li>
        <li>5 tablespoons olive oil, or whichever fat you prefer</li>
        <li>Handful of rosemary and parsley, or other herbs, finely chopped</li>
        <li>3 cloves garlic, minced</li>
        <li>Black pepper, to taste</li>
        <li>Salt, to taste</li>
    </ul>

    <h3><strong>Directions</strong></h3>
    <ol>
        <li>Preheat oven to 450F and bring 2 litres of water to a boil over high heat.</li>
        <li>Add the baking soda and a pinch of salt to the water, along with the potatoes. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer. Cook for until potatoes can be easily peirced by a fork or knife, about 10 minutes</li>
        <li>While the potatoes are boiling, combine the olive oil, rosemary, garlic, and black pepper in a small saucepan over medium heat. Cooking, stirring constantly, until the garlic is browned, about 3 minutes. Strain through a fine-mesh strainer and set aside. Reserve the strained garlic and rosemary, as we will use it again later.</li>
        <li>Carefully drain the potatoes and let them sit until they stop steaming. Transfer to a bowl along with the infused oil, season with more salt and pepper, and shake the bowl to roughen up the potatoe pieces. The goal is to shake as much as you can without turning them completely into mashed potatoes. You want the pieces to be clearly individual, but with a very mushy exterior.</li>
        <li>Transfer potatoes to a baking sheet, spread them out, and cook without moving them for 20 minutes in your preheated oven. After 20 minutes, stir the potatoes well, some may be stuck to the pan, make sure to release them all. Continue cooking for an additional 30-40 minutes, stirring occasionally, until potatoes are well done.</li>
        <li>Add the reserved garlic and rosemary back to the potatoes and taste for seasoning. Enjoy!</li>
    </ol>
</div>
